comments.comment_body:
Panem and Circences led to the fall of the Roman Empire;
Bread and Games for the plebe, that will make them happy and the decadent emperors who bought their crown by paying the legions will continue to rule until the whole fundamentally unstable system finally  crumbles.
For us, it is low wages ( bread)  and media entertainemnt (circenses);
The fact that now days you can buy a gas gugling car because you are driven by stupid and lying advertisements ( buy a car  which  is bigger than yours neighbour's) does not change the panem aspect of the" deal", which is to let the present elite, political and finacial, continue to rule
Be happy whith what we condescent to give you and let us be billionnaires emperors.
Are we not generous, we GiVE you work. Say thank you as you would if we gave you a brand new car...

“A sustainable decadence, if you will, in which the crucial task for 21st-century humanity would be making the most of a prosperous stagnation: 
learning to temper our expectations and live within limits; (as in reducing carbon emissions);
making sure existing resources are distributed more justly; (as in a 1 percent wealth tax, and Medicare-for-All);
using education to lift people into the sunlit uplands of the creative class; (as in free college and no college debt);
and doing everything we can to help poorer countries transition successfully into our current position, (as in JFK’s Peace Corps, UNICEF, Doctors Without Borders, and many NGOs).”

It seems that decadence is a precondition for bringing the kingdom of heaven to earth.

That only in the surfeit and boredom of decadence will people finally get around to seeing their struggling poor at the bottom.

A CNBC clip suggested the stock market has already absorbed a potential Sanders win — Medicare for All and Free College are likely good for the economy, and for society.
 People will move more often to find a better job without risking loss of health care coverage in their current dead-end jub. Young people will marry sooner and have more children because they won’t have college debt, nor need to save for college.
And we need more public housing for the homeless.
